aws-transcripts.transcript: I grew up on a small farm in Missouri. We lived on less than a dollar a day for about 15 years. I got a scholarship, went to university, studied international agriculture, studied anthropology and decided I was gonna give back. I was gonna work with small farmers. I was gonna help alleviate poverty. I was gonna work on international development. And then I took a turn and ended up here. Now, if you get a phD and you decide not to teach, you don't always end up in a place like this. It's a choice. You might end up driving a taxicab. You could be in New York. What I found was I started working with refugees and famine victims, small farmers, all or nearly all who had been dispossessed and displaced. Now, what I've been trained to do was method a logical research on such people. So I did it. I found out how many women had been raped in route to these camps. I found out how many people had been put in jail. How many family members had been killed. I assessed how long they were going to stay and how much it would take to feed them, and I got really good at predicting how many body bags she would need for the people who were gonna die in these camps. Now, this is God's work, but it's not. My work is not the work I set out to do. So I was at a Grateful Dead Benefit concert on the rain forest, 1988. I met a guy, the guy on the left. His name was Ben. He said, What can I do to save the rain forest? I said, Well, Ben, what do you do? I make ice cream. So I said, Well, you've got to make a rain forest ice cream and you got to use nuts from the rainforest to show that forest are more worth more. As for us than they are his pasture, he said. Okay, Within a year, Rainforest Crunch was on the shelves. It was a great success. We did our 1st $1,000,000 worth of trade by buying on 30 days and selling on 21 that gets your adrenaline going. Then we had a four and 1/2 $1,000,000 line of credit because we were creditworthy. At that point, we had 15 to 20 maybe 22% of the global Brazil nut market. We paid 2 to 3 times more than anybody else. Everybody else raised their prices to together's of Brazil nuts because we would buy it otherwise, a great success. 50 companies signed up, 200 products came out generated 100,000,000 in sales. It failed. Why did it fail? Because the people who were gathering Brazil nuts weren't the same people who were cutting the forced and the people who made money from Brazil. Nuts were not the people who made money from cutting the forced. We were attacking the wrong driver. We needed to be working on beef. We need to be working on lumber. We need to be working on soy things that we were not focused on. So let's go back to Sudan. I often talk to refugees. Why was it that the West didn't realize that famines, air caused by policies and politics, not by weather? And this farmer said to me one day something was very profound. He said, You can't wake a person who's pretending to sleep. Okay, Fast forward. We live on a planet. There's just one of them. We've gotta wake up to the fact that we don't have any more and that this is a finite planet. We know the limits of the resource is we have. We may be able to use them differently. We may have some innovative new ideas, but in general this is what we got. There's no more of it. There's a basic equation that we can't get away from population times.
